# First-Time Setup Guide

## When to trigger setup

Check if the file `.designer` exists in the repo root. If it **does not exist**, the user has not completed setup yet. When they ask to "set up" or "get started" or paste a getting-started prompt, walk them through the setup flow below.

If `.designer` already exists, setup is done -- skip this entirely and follow the normal `design-tool.mdc` rules.

## Detecting setup type

There are two setup paths. Detect which one based on what the user says:

- **Company setup** -- they say things like "setting up for my company", "first time", or they cloned from the original `BUnglaub/design-core` repo. They're the first person at their org. They need the full setup: fork to their org, identity, company info, team members.
- **Designer joining** -- they say things like "joining my team", "my company already has this", or they cloned from their org's fork (not `BUnglaub/design-core`). They just need their personal identity set up.

You can also detect this by checking the git remote: run `git remote -v`. If the origin points to `BUnglaub/design-core`, this is a company setup. If it points to another org, this is a designer joining.

If unclear, ask: "Are you setting this up for your company for the first time, or joining a team that already has it?"

## Setup flow

Walk the user through these steps conversationally. Ask one thing at a time -- don't dump everything at once. Be friendly and non-technical.

### 1. Clone the repo

If the repo isn't already cloned and open in Cursor, clone it for them. The user's prompt should include the repo URL. Clone it to a sensible location (e.g. `~/Documents` or `~/Projects`), then open the folder in Cursor.

### 2. Install Node.js

Run `node --version` to check if Node.js is installed. If it's not:
- On macOS: try `brew install node`. If Homebrew isn't installed either, guide them to download Node.js from [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org).
- On Windows/Linux: guide them to download from [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org) (LTS version).

### 3. Install dependencies

Run `npm install` for them. Wait for it to finish. If it fails, help troubleshoot.

### 4. Company setup: fork to their org

**This step only applies to company setup (first person at the org).**

The user cloned the original `BUnglaub/design-core` repo. They need their own copy under their GitHub org so their team can collaborate. Walk them through this:

1. Ask: **"What's your GitHub organization or account name?"** (e.g. `acme-design`)
2. Help them create a fork or new repo under their org. They can:
   - Go to `https://github.com/BUnglaub/design-core` and click **Fork**, choosing their org as the owner
   - Or create a new repo on GitHub and push to it
3. Once they have their org's repo URL, update the git remote:
   ```
   git remote set-url origin https://github.com/THEIR_ORG/design-core.git
   ```
4. Update `GETTING_STARTED.md` -- replace `YOUR_ORG` in the designer joining prompt with their actual org name, so when teammates read the page they get the right clone URL
5. Commit and push these changes to their new repo

Skip this step entirely for designers joining -- they already cloned from their org's fork.

### 5. Collect identity info

#### Company setup (first person at the org)

Ask the user:

1. **"What's your name?"** -- their display name for attribution on projects
2. **"What's your company or team name?"** -- the organization using Design Core
3. **"Who else is on your design team?"** -- optional, they can add people later. If they provide names, collect them.

Create `.designer` in the repo root:

```json
{
  "name": "Their Name",
  "company": "Their Company",
  "team": [
    { "name": "Their Name" },
    { "name": "Teammate 1" },
    { "name": "Teammate 2" }
  ]
}
```

Also update `.designer.example` so future teammates see the right format with the company name pre-filled:

```json
{
  "name": "Your Name",
  "company": "Their Company",
  "team": [
    { "name": "Your Name" }
  ]
}
```

Commit the updated `.designer.example` to git so teammates get it when they clone.

#### Designer joining (team already exists)

Ask the user:

1. **"What's your name?"** -- their display name for attribution

Read `.designer.example` to get the company name and pre-fill it. If the example file doesn't have a company name, ask them.

Create `.designer` in the repo root:

```json
{
  "name": "Their Name",
  "company": "Company from .designer.example",
  "team": [
    { "name": "Their Name" }
  ]
}
```

The team array only needs them -- they don't need to list the whole org. The `company` field should match what the admin set up.

### 6. Start the preview server

Run `npm run dev` and tell them the URL to open in their browser. Explain what they'll see: the home page with a project hub.

### 7. Offer next steps

#### For company setup

> "You're all set! A few things you might want to do:
> - **Create your first project** -- just tell me a name and I'll set it up
> - **Share with your team** -- send them the Getting Started page on your repo: `https://github.com/THEIR_ORG/design-core/blob/main/GETTING_STARTED.md` -- the designer joining prompt already has your org's repo link.
> - **Explore the design system** -- click Design System in the nav to see available components
>
> What would you like to do first?"

#### For designer joining

> "You're all set! Here's what you can do:
> - **Create a project** -- just tell me a name and I'll set it up
> - **Look at existing projects** -- check the home page to see what your team has built
> - **Explore the design system** -- click Design System in the nav to see available components
>
> What would you like to build?"

## Important notes

- The `.designer` file is gitignored -- each person on the team creates their own when they first set up
- `.designer.example` IS committed to git -- the admin updates it with the company name so new designers get it pre-filled
- `GETTING_STARTED.md` IS committed to git -- the admin updates it with their org's repo URL so designers get the right clone link
- The `company` field helps the AI understand the team context
- The `team` array is a local reference -- each person's file only needs their own name (the admin's file may list everyone)
- Do NOT commit `.designer` to git. Only `.designer.example` gets committed.
